NAME
    tset(1)		- setup the TERM environment variable

SYNOPSIS
    eval `tset  [ device_type ]`

DESCRIPTION
    This command is generally used in a ".profile" script
    with no arguments. In this case tset(1) uses the name
    of the current port and looks in "/etc/ttytype" to find
    the default device type for the port. It will return a
    "TERM=..." definition for export. Put the following in
    your ".profile" script:

		eval `tset`

    If the optional "device_type" is supplied then tset(1)
    will generate a "TERM=device_type" string. However, to 
    change the current device type it is easier to simply
    type the "TERM=..." parameter yourself.

    Tset(1) checks to make sure the device has a description
    in "/etc/termcap".

    The command stty(1) should be used to set the terminal
    characteristics, for example the "line kill" character.

FILES
    /etc/termcap	definitions for termcap(3)
    /etc/ttytype 	device type at each port

SEE ALSO
    stty(1), environ(4), termcap(4), ttytype(4)
